    "num": "13",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">13</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Source Criticism</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Evaluating Primary and Secondary Sources</h2><ul><li>Primary sources: court records, depositions, official documents</li><li>Secondary sources: scholarly analyses, summaries, interpretations</li><li>Assess bias, purpose, and audience of each source</li><li>Identify gaps and inconsistencies in records</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Understanding the nature of primary and secondary sources is essential to critically evaluate the evidence about the Ingalls family and the witch trials. Primary sources provide direct evidence but may have biases or gaps, while secondary sources interpret these records and can introduce their own perspectives. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s4\">[4]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s12\">[12]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Compare a court transcript naming Martha Ingalls with a later historian’s interpretation of her role to identify potential bias or assumptions.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Review a provided excerpt from a trial record and a secondary summary; note differences in tone, detail, and possible bias.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming all primary sources are unbiased or all secondary sources are unreliable without critical evaluation.</p></div></div>",
