    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">14</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Genealogical Challenges</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Name Confusion and Family Identification</h2><ul><li>Multiple individuals with similar names in 1692 Salem records</li><li>Distinguishing Ingalls family members requires cross-referencing</li><li>Common errors arise from conflating different people</li><li>Importance of verifying dates, locations, and relationships</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">The Ingalls family name appears in various records, but identifying which individuals relate directly to the witch trials is complex. Researchers must carefully cross-check genealogical data to avoid conflating separate persons or family lines. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s4\">[4]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Comparing trial records mentioning 'Martha Ingalls' with genealogical data to confirm her identity as Martha Ingalls Allen Carrier.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Given two similar names in records, decide which likely refers to the Ingalls family member involved in the trials.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming all references to 'Ingalls' in 1692 Salem refer to the same family or individual.</p></div></div>",
