    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">16</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Legal and Religious Context</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Puritan Beliefs and Witchcraft Laws</h2><ul><li>Witchcraft defined as a crime against God and community</li><li>Puritan theology shaped interpretation of evidence</li><li>Legal standards included spectral evidence and confessions</li><li>Trials reflected religious and social control mechanisms</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">The witch trials were deeply rooted in Puritan religious beliefs and legal frameworks that criminalized witchcraft as a spiritual and social threat. Understanding these frameworks is key to interpreting trial proceedings and accusations. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s15\">[15]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Examining how spectral evidence was used to convict accused witches despite its controversial nature.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Discuss how Puritan beliefs influenced the acceptance of certain types of evidence in trials.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Applying modern legal standards retroactively to 17th-century trials.</p></div></div>",
