    "id": "slide21",
    "eyebrow": "Communicating History",
    "num": "21",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">21</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Communicating History</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Crafting Evidence-Based Summaries</h2><ul><li>Use cautious language to reflect uncertainty</li><li>Distinguish between fact, inference, and speculation</li><li>Avoid overstating unverified claims</li><li>Tailor communication for general audiences</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Effective historical communication requires balancing clarity with honesty about evidentiary limits, especially when discussing contested topics like the Ingalls family’s role in the witch trials. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s12\">[12]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Rewriting a dramatic family legend into a fact-based summary with qualifiers.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Draft a brief summary of the Ingalls family’s involvement using cautious language.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Presenting uncertain or disputed information as definitive fact.</p></div><div id=\"quiz-slide21\" class=\"quizbox popquiz anim\" data-quiz=\"[{&quot;type&quot;:&quot;mc&quot;,&quot;level&quot;:2,&quot;q&quot;:&quot;Which source type provides the most direct evidence about the Ingalls family&#39;s role in the 1692 witch trials?&quot;,&quot;options&quot;:[&quot;Primary court records and trial transcripts&quot;,&quot;Modern historical interpretations&quot;,&quot;Family folklore and oral traditions&quot;,&quot;Popular media dramatizations&quot;],&quot;answer&quot;:0,&quot;why&quot;:&quot;Primary court records and trial transcripts are original documents from the time of the trials and offer direct evidence, unlike later interpretations or folklore.&quot;},{&quot;type&quot;:&quot;sa&quot;,&quot;level&quot;:3,&quot;q&quot;:&quot;Explain why it is important to use cautious language when summarizing the Ingalls family&#39;s involvement in the Salem witch trials.&quot;,&quot;rubric&quot;:&quot;The answer should mention the limits of historical records, potential biases in sources, name confusion, and the need to avoid overstating uncertain or unsupported claims.&quot;,&quot;sample&quot;:&quot;Because historical records about the Ingalls family are incomplete and sometimes conflicting, cautious language helps avoid presenting uncertain or disputed information as fact.&quot;,&quot;accept&quot;:[&quot;Historical records are incomplete and biased, so cautious language prevents overstating facts.&quot;,&quot;Name confusion and missing evidence require careful wording to avoid misleading conclusions.&quot;,&quot;To reflect uncertainty and avoid presenting unverified claims as truth.&quot;]}]\" data-pop=\"1\"></div></div>",
    "paper": {
      "secnum": "Deep Dive 21",
      "h": "Deep Dive: Best Practices in Historical Communication",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Effective historical communication requires balancing clarity with honesty about evidentiary limits, especially when discussing contested topics like the Ingalls family’s role in the witch trials.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from cpalms.org. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Use cautious language to reflect uncertainty</li><li>Distinguish between fact, inference, and speculation</li><li>Avoid overstating unverified claims</li><li>Tailor communication for general audiences</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Rewriting a dramatic family legend into a fact-based summary with qualifiers.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Draft a brief summary of the Ingalls family’s involvement using cautious language.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Presenting uncertain or disputed information as definitive fact.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> cpalms.org <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s12\">[12]</sup></p>"
    }
