      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Comparing different types of narratives about the Ingalls family helps learners distinguish between evidence-based history and storytelling. This comparison highlights how myths can arise and persist.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from history.com; youtube.com; decortoadore.net. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Scholarly works emphasize evidence and uncertainty</li><li>Popular retellings often dramatize or mythologize events</li><li>Family lore may conflate individuals or exaggerate roles</li><li>Critical comparison reveals discrepancies and clarifies facts</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>A popular narrative may claim the Ingalls family were central victims, while scholarly sources show limited direct involvement beyond Martha Ingalls Allen Carrier.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Examine two contrasting accounts of the Ingalls family and identify which claims are supported by primary evidence.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Accepting popular or family stories as historical fact without verification.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> history.com; youtube.com; decortoadore.net <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s3\">[3]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p>"
