    "num": "27",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">27</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Genealogical Verification</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Confirming Ingalls Family Identities in Records</h2><ul><li>Multiple individuals named Ingalls complicate identification</li><li>Cross-referencing trial documents with genealogical data is essential</li><li>Name spelling variations and record gaps cause confusion</li><li>Careful analysis prevents misattributing events or roles</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Accurately identifying which Ingalls family members appear in witch trial records requires careful genealogical research and cross-checking with trial documents to avoid errors. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s4\">[4]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Matching Martha Ingalls Allen Carrier’s trial records with genealogical data confirms her identity and family connections.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Given sample records with similar names, determine which belong to the Ingalls family involved in the trials.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming all references to 'Ingalls' refer to the same person or family line.</p></div></div>",
