      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> This practice helps learners critically analyze narratives and avoid conflating legend with fact.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from history.com; youtube.com; decortoadore.net. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Identify elements likely based on documented evidence</li><li>Spot details that appear exaggerated or fictionalized</li><li>Consider the origin and purpose of each narrative</li><li>Use evidence to support or question claims</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>A story portraying the Ingalls family as central victims may be popular but lacks corroboration in trial records.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Analyze a narrative passage and classify statements as fact-based or legend-based.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Accepting dramatic stories without critical evaluation.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> history.com; youtube.com; decortoadore.net <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s3\">[3]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p>"
